title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: OmicsQC package designed analyze quality control metrics multi-sample studies nominate putative outlier samples exclusion using unbiased statistical approaches. package can subdivided three parts: quality score calculation, outlier detection, data visualization. flowchart illustrates parts interact flow data throughout package. package comes example data, consisting 100 samples recent profiling study scored according 26 quality control metrics.

code: library(OmicsQC);  # Loading Data data('example.qc.dataframe'); # Metric scores across samples data('sign.correction'); # The directionality of metrics data('ylabels'); # Formatted metric labels for heatmap

title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: package designed independent test metrics used, since test metrics better larger better smaller, sign poor z-score differ metrics. must therefore adjust metrics negative z-scores considered bad measurement across tests. function correct.zscore.signs requires input states positive negative z-score good metric. input takes form dataframe column metric column sign potential values ‘pos’ ‘neg’ metric used. function correct.zscore.signs also sets non-negative z-scores zero make sure positive negative values cancel calculate accumulated score. Apart zscores, signs.data, function also takes names columns containing metric name sign instructions sign.data. output function, zscores.corrected, can now used calculate accumulated scores sample.
code: zscores.corrected <- correct.zscore.signs(   zscores = zscores,   signs.data = sign.correction,   metric.col.name = 'Metric',   signs.col.name = 'Sign'   );

title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: accumulate.zscores takes zscores.corrected dataframe calculates total quality score sample. summing negative z-scores. orders data magnitude quality score returns result dataframe. resulting quality.scores shown :
code: quality.scores <- accumulate.zscores(zscores.corrected = zscores.corrected);

title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: second part package offers distribution fitting outlier detection using two implementations cosine outlier detection method. based cosine similarity, two implementations offer pros cons. Generally speaking, cutoff method low sensitivity high precision, iterative method high sensitivity low precision.

what: The iterative method for outlier nomination using cosine similarity
title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: function cosine.similarity.iterative takes quality.scores, trims proportion data indicated trim.factor extreme, fits distribution given. tests largest datapoint compared null distribution size .simulations. largest datapoint significant p-value, moves onto 2nd largest datapoint , reaches datapoint whose p-value insignificant. Number outliers found: sample labels outliers:
code: outlier.detect.iterative.res <- cosine.similarity.iterative(     quality.scores = quality.scores,     distribution = 'lnorm',     no.simulations = 1000,     trim.factor = 0.15,     alpha.significant = 0.05     ); print(outlier.detect.iterative.res$no.outliers); #> [1] 11 print(outlier.detect.iterative.res$outlier.labels); #>  [1] "CPCG0375" "CPCG0382" "CPCG0498" "CPCG0464" "CPCG0437" "CPCG0235" #>  [7] "CPCG0486" "CPCG0263" "CPCG0266" "CPCG0256" "CPCG0502"

what: The cutoff method for outlier nomination using cosine similarity
title: Introduction to omicsQC
text: function cosine.similarity.cutoff takes quality.scores, trims proportion data indicated trim.factor extreme, fits distribution given. simulates many datasets stated .simulations, computes cosine similarity dataset theoretical distribution. Using simulatd dataset, estimates cutoff threshold cosine similarity correspond statistically significant p-value (determined alpha.significant) nominates outliers surpass threshold. Quality score cutoff: Number outliers found: sample labels outliers:
code: outlier.detect.cutoff.res <- cosine.similarity.cutoff(     quality.scores = quality.scores,     distribution = 'lnorm',     no.simulations = 1000,     trim.factor = 0.15,     alpha.significant = 0.05     ); print(outlier.detect.cutoff.res$cutoff); #>       5%  #> 24.58138 print(outlier.detect.cutoff.res$no.outliers); #> [1] 6 print(outlier.detect.cutoff.res$outlier.labels); #> [1] "CPCG0235" "CPCG0437" "CPCG0464" "CPCG0498" "CPCG0382" "CPCG0375"
